english:
  title: A Farewell to Kim Kyeun Upon His Departure to Serve as Deputy Under the Observers of Chungcheong
  author: Kim Gam
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Kim Kyeun of Buseong had served as Provincial Inspector of Pyeongan, but finding himself too far from home, he petitioned the court for reassignment to Chungcheong. As he prepared to depart, I hastened to bid him farewell. He said to me, "Rather than lament our parting, would you not compose something for me?" I replied, "The Provincial Observer commands full authority over his region and wields power over appointments and dismissals. You, as his deputy, become the chief administrator of the province, participating in every decision, great and small. Your rank is humble, yet your burden is heavy; your responsibility is stringent. Now that you depart, I wish to know your resolve."

    Kyeun said, "Someone told me that a deputy inspector serves to bridge the higher and lower ranks. I do not concern myself greatly with this." I responded, "Such words contain wisdom, and my own remarks do not exceed them. The matter rests upon how you reconcile these views."

    Consider this: the deputy inspector holds rank of the fifth degree, equal to county magistrates, yet participates in the Provincial Observer's assessments of officials' merit and demerit, passing judgment on the virtue or corruption of provincial administrators. Though fifth rank places one among county magistrates, the power to evaluate all officials from prefects downward makes his authority second only to the Observer. Thus, from the mayors of provinces below, none dare stand as equals. By this measure, indeed, one might say he bridges the higher and lower.

    The court ever sought capable administrators close to the people, yet even among the central bureaucracy, talent cannot be fully secured. How much less can the distant provinces and remote counties boast of virtuous magistrates? The paths to office are many—through inherited position, through clerical ranks—and ignorant scribes often don the robes of office. Yet people of this age revere antiquity while disdaining their own time. When such disdain is joined with the power to judge others, and when an official sits in judgment over magistrates he deems unworthy, it is like yoking a lame horse to a cart while men like Wang Liang and Zao Fu crack the whip above it. Would not such a horse grow despondent and shirk its duty? Even knowing it is judged inferior, it stumbles and strays, unable to reach distant lands.

    True thoroughbreds are rare in this world. We can only hope to coax excellence from common steeds. Yet hear this: when deputy and Observer are of one mind, all succeeds; when divided, all fails. Failing, one merely processes documents and adds one's seal—a shadow play that brings only laughter.

    You, my friend, are broadly learned, skilled in letters, advanced through examinations, versed in human affairs and current administration. Your path resembles that of the ancients themselves. Even to enter an official's household as advisor seems inadequate recompense for your talents. How then should I burden you with lengthy words? And moreover, you serve under Lord Cao of Maegye—a statesman of the highest order. I foresee that the provinces will flourish, all prefectures will find peace, and the winds and moonlight of the southern lands will henceforth yield their bounty not to idle poets but to good governance.

    I offer this farewell in the spirit of those elder words, expressing my joy that such talent serves the Prime Minister. Should your rounds take you through Jecheon, I ask that you bring word of my wellbeing to your travels.
  footnotes:
    - Wang Liang and Zao Fu were legendary charioteers and horsemasters of ancient China, known for their extraordinary skill in managing horses. The comparison suggests that even expert guidance cannot transform an inferior instrument.
    - Lord Cao of Maegye (梅溪曹相國) appears to be the Provincial Observer whom Kim Kyeun will serve—a figure of considerable reputation and ability.
    - The reference to 'Ma Cao's reply' and 'holding a scepter' alludes to officials who communicate through rigid formality rather than genuine engagement with their duties.
    - Jecheon (堤川) is a location the poem's author asks Kim Kyeun to pass through, suggesting his route of travel.
